    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, our lineup leans heavily into favorable matchups against soft-tossing right-handers and high-value spots at the top of the order. **Trea Turner** (79.76) and **Kyle Schwarber** (78.40) headline our offense, both enjoying an elite matchup against Mart\u00edn P\u00e9rez. **Turner** is our primary engine today, benefiting from a +19% boost due to SP skill and his position atop the order, while **Schwarber** remains a must-start with an elite 0.402 xwOBA. **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (74.17) rounds out our top-tier plays; his +14% platoon edge against Senga makes him a high-efficiency play despite the lower lineup spot, provided he maintains his role on the basepaths. Additionally, **Hyeseong Kim** (70.52) benefits from a significant +17% boost against the mediocre expected ERA of Tomoyuki Sugano, making him an unexpected anchor in the middle of our order.\n\nThe most difficult decision on today\u2019s bench was **Victor Scott II** (48.83). While his speed profile is exactly what we crave, the optimizer penalized his likely #9 spot in the order, which caps his R/RBI ceiling too severely to displace higher-scoring bats like **Jerar Encarnacion** or **Carson Benge**. Meanwhile, **Junior Caminero** (55.02) remains in our starting lineup despite a -19% penalty against the difficult arm of Bubba Chandler; his base projection is simply too high to bench, but he is a candidate for early-inning removal if he struggles against early breakers. We continue to monitor the \"Lineup Pending\" status for several hitters, most notably **Gary Sanchez** and **Dillon Dingler**; should either fall out of the projected #4 spot, we may see further volatility in their efficiency scores. Finally, please note that **Zac Veen** remains unavailable in the Minors, and we continue to wait for further updates on **Christian Yelich**, **Lars Nootbaar**, and **Luis Pena** as they work through their respective status changes.",
